{"cursor":"22318","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n, uncut sapphire, ruby, uncut emerald, and uncut amethyst.]]\n\nA 'gemstone' or 'gem' (also called a 'precious' or 'semi-precious stone', a\n'fine gem', or 'jewel') is a piece of mineral, which, in cut and polished form,\nis used to make jewelry or other adornments. [http://www.askoxford.com The\nOxford Dictionary Online] and [http://mw1.merriam-\nwebster.com/dictionary/gemstone Webster Online Dictionary]\nHowever certain rocks (such as lapis lazuli), or organic materials that are not\nminerals (such as amber or jet), are also used for jewelry, and are therefore\noften considered to be gemstones as well. Most gemstones are hard, but some soft\nminerals are used in jewelry because of their luster or other physical\nproperties that have aesthetic value. Rarity is another characteristic that\nlends value to a gemstone. Apart from jewelry, from earliest antiquity until the\n19th century engraved gems and hardstone carvings such as cups were major luxury\nart forms; the carvings of Carl FabergÃ© were the last significant works in this\ntradition.\n","linknr":518,"url":"Hybrid_gemstone","recorded":1362543216,"links":81,"instances":["lignite","geology","mineral","mineralogy","optics","crystal"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Gemstones|","Jewellery components","Materials","Mineralogy","Minerals|*","Body modification"],"headings":["Characteristics and classification","Value","Grading","Cutting and polishing","Color","Treatment","Synthetic and artificial gemstones","See also","Notes","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Cardinal_gems.png/250px-Cardinal_gems.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/Gem.pebbles.800pix.labelled.jpg/250px-Gem.pebbles.800pix.labelled.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipe